Good approach — inspect fully before deleting. Here's the complete pre-deletion investigation, split into what to pull from the cluster, what your chart will render, and how to compare them.

## Step 1 — Capture the live ClusterRoleBinding from the cluster

Dump the full object and a clean copy (stripped of runtime noise) for comparison:

```bash
# Full live object, as-is
oc get clusterrolebinding dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view -o yaml > /tmp/crb-live-full.yaml

# Clean copy (drop server-managed fields) for a fair diff against chart output
oc get clusterrolebinding dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view -o yaml \
  | grep -vE '^\s*(uid|resourceVersion|creationTimestamp|generation|managedFields:|time:|manager:|operation:|apiVersion: .*/v1$)' \
  > /tmp/crb-live-raw.yaml

cat /tmp/crb-live-full.yaml
```

The three fields that matter most for the comparison — who it binds, to what role, and who owns it:

```bash
echo "== roleRef (the ClusterRole it grants) =="
oc get clusterrolebinding dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view -o jsonpath='{.roleRef.kind}/{.roleRef.name}{"\n"}'

echo "== subjects (who receives the permission) =="
oc get clusterrolebinding dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view -o jsonpath='{range .subjects[*]}{.kind}{" "}{.namespace}{"/"}{.name}{"\n"}{end}'

echo "== ownership metadata (is anything managing it?) =="
oc get clusterrolebinding dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view \
  -o jsonpath='managed-by={.metadata.labels.app\.kubernetes\.io/managed-by}{"\n"}release={.metadata.annotations.meta\.helm\.sh/release-name}{"\n"}ownerRefs={.metadata.ownerReferences}{"\n"}'
```

## Step 2 — Render what your Helm chart *would* create

Render just this one template so you compare the same object:

```bash
cd /tmp/dep/deployment-main/dev/charts/epay_common

helm template epay-common . \
  --namespace dev-epay-common \
  --show-only templates/kiali/kiali-clusterrolebinding.yaml \
  > /tmp/crb-chart.yaml

cat /tmp/crb-chart.yaml
```

If your CI passes an env values file, add `-f <that file>` so the render matches production reality. If `helm template` isn't in the runner, substitute `helm secrets template` or whatever your pipeline uses — the point is to render with the *same* values the deploy job uses.

## Step 3 — Compare live vs chart, field by field

```bash
echo "===== roleRef ====="
diff <(grep -A3 '^roleRef:' /tmp/crb-live-raw.yaml) \
     <(grep -A3 '^roleRef:' /tmp/crb-chart.yaml)

echo "===== subjects ====="
diff <(sed -n '/^subjects:/,/^roleRef:/p' /tmp/crb-live-raw.yaml) \
     <(sed -n '/^subjects:/,/^roleRef:/p' /tmp/crb-chart.yaml)

echo "===== full side-by-side ====="
diff -y --suppress-common-lines /tmp/crb-live-raw.yaml /tmp/crb-chart.yaml
```

**What you're looking for.** The only *acceptable* differences are the ownership metadata (labels/annotations Helm will add). If `roleRef.name`, the subject `ServiceAccount` name, or its `namespace` differ between live and chart, **do not delete yet** — the chart would recreate a binding with different semantics, and deletion followed by a mismatched recreate could leave Kiali without the monitoring-view permission it currently has.

Note from the chart I already reviewed: the `monitoring` CRB template renders **no** `labels`/`annotations` blocks (unlike the viewer/oauth siblings), so a chart-created copy will still lack the Helm ownership metadata unless you harden the template first (Step 6). That's worth fixing in the same change.

## Step 4 — Understand the blast radius before deleting

`cluster-monitoring-view` is the OpenShift built-in ClusterRole that grants read access to the cluster monitoring stack (Prometheus/Thanos). This binding is what lets Kiali pull metrics to draw its service-mesh graphs and health.

Check what actually depends on it:

```bash
# Which ServiceAccount holds this grant, and does Kiali reference it?
oc get clusterrolebinding dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view -o jsonpath='{.subjects}' ; echo

# Is the ServiceAccount real and in use by the Kiali pod?
oc get sa dev-kiali-service-account -n dev-istio-system 2>/dev/null || echo "SA not in that ns — check subjects output above"
oc get pods -n dev-istio-system -l app.kubernetes.io/name=kiali -o name

# Is a Kiali OPERATOR managing this? (decisive — see below)
oc get kiali -A 2>/dev/null
oc get clusterrolebinding dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view -o jsonpath='{.metadata.ownerReferences}' ; echo
```

**Impact of deleting it:**

During the window between `oc delete` and the Helm recreate, the Kiali ServiceAccount loses cluster-monitoring-view. In practice Kiali's **metrics/graph panels stop returning data** and may log authz errors; the Kiali pod itself keeps running (this is RBAC, not the deployment). Once Helm recreates the binding, access is restored — RBAC changes take effect near-immediately, no pod restart needed. So the impact is a brief loss of Kiali monitoring visibility, **not** an outage of any payment service. Nothing in the transaction path depends on this binding.

**The one thing that changes the plan:** if `oc get kiali -A` returns a CR **and** the `ownerReferences` on the CRB point to it, then the **Kiali operator owns this object**. In that case:
- The operator will likely **recreate it unlabeled** the moment you delete it, immediately reintroducing the same Helm conflict — deletion won't fix anything.
- You'd have two controllers fighting for one cluster-scoped resource.

If that's the case, don't sync it into Helm at all — instead remove the CRB from the chart and let the operator own it, or scope the operator so Helm can own it. Decide on a single owner.

## Step 5 — Safe deletion + sync sequence (operator is *not* the owner)

Only if Step 4 confirms no operator ownership and Step 3 shows semantics match:

```bash
# Backup already saved at /tmp/crb-live-full.yaml — keep it
# Delete the orphan
oc delete clusterrolebinding dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view

# Re-run the deploy pipeline job — Helm recreates it, now release-owned
# Verify adoption:
oc get clusterrolebinding dev-kiali-cluster-monitoring-view \
  -o jsonpath='managed-by={.metadata.labels.app\.kubernetes\.io/managed-by}{" release="}{.metadata.annotations.meta\.helm\.sh/release-name}{"\n"}'
```

If you'd rather avoid even the brief permission gap, use the **adopt-in-place** method from before (`oc annotate` + `oc label`) instead of delete — same end state, zero gap. Deletion is only necessary if you specifically want a from-scratch recreate.

## Step 6 — Harden the template so this never recurs

Add ownership-friendly metadata to `templates/kiali/kiali-clusterrolebinding.yaml` so future fresh clusters get labelled bindings and adoption is always clean:

```yaml
metadata:
  name: {{ .Values.monitoring.kiali.rbac.clusterRoleBindings.monitoring.name }}
  labels:
    {{- toYaml .Values.monitoring.kiali.rbac.labels | nindent 4 }}
  annotations:
    {{- toYaml .Values.monitoring.kiali.rbac.annotations | nindent 4 }}
```

This mirrors what the `viewer` and `oauth` templates already do, so the three bindings stay consistent.

Run Steps 1–4 first and paste the diff and the `oc get kiali -A` / `ownerReferences` output back here — that determines whether you go the delete route or must hand ownership to the operator.
